metadata.title: Stinson 108
aws::graph::propositions: Two prototype model 108s were converted from Stinson model 10A airframes.
FAA records show NX31519 was model 108 serial number 1.
FAA records show NX31532 is model 108 serial number 2.
Both prototype registrations later changed from NX to NC.
The production model straight 108 would also use serial number 1 and 2.
There was for a short period 2 duplicate serial numbers.
The 108 Voyager 125 is a variant of the Stinson 108.
The 108 Voyager 125 is powered by a 125 hp (93 kW) Lycoming O-235 piston engine.
The 108 Voyager 150 is a variant of the Stinson 108.
The 108 Voyager 150 is powered by a 150 hp (112 kW) Franklin 6A4-150-B31, B3 or B4 piston engine.
742 units of the 108 Voyager 150 were built in 1946.
The 108-1 is a variant of the Stinson 108.
The 108-1 is a slightly modified version with external baggage door.
1508 units of the 108-1 were built between 1947 and 1948.
The 108 variants closely resemble each other but can be visually distinguished by their design changes.

text:
## Variants

The 108 variants closely resemble each other but can be visually distinguished by their design changes:

Prototype 108
Two prototype model 108s were converted from Stinson model 10A airframes. FAA records show NX31519 was model 108 serial number 1, and NX31532 is model 108 serial number 2.  Both registrations later changed to NC. The production model straight 108 would also use serial number 1 and 2, so there was for a short period 2 duplicate serial numbers;
108 Voyager 125
Powered by a 125 hp (93 kW) Lycoming O-235 piston engine.
108 Voyager 150
Powered by a 150 hp (112 kW) Franklin 6A4-150-B31, B3 or B4 piston engine. 742 built in 1946.
108-1
Slightly modified version with external baggage door. 1508 built 19471948.
